  <h1>1. Executive Project Overview & Business Value</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    In modern contact center operations, quality assurance (QA) is a critical compliance and coaching vector. Historically, supervisors had to manually listen to voice recordings or scan plain transcripts to audit conversations. This process is time-consuming, subjective, and difficult to scale.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <strong>Call Quality Review Tool</strong> solves this issue by introducing automated, real-time voice intelligence. By integrating advanced machine learning transcription, speaker diarization, deterministic conversational pattern scanning, and LLM-driven feedback, the application automatically flags critical events.
  </p>
  <p>
    This documentation manual serves as a complete blueprint of the platform. It covers everything from high-performance 3D card tilt handlers to LLM diarization prompting, demonstrating how to build a production-grade voice analytics dashboard using modern full-stack web standards.
  </p>

  <h2>Key Architectural Objectives:</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High Performance:</strong> Deliver sub-second DOM modifications and client-side document exports without external dependencies.</li>
    <li><strong>Robust Transcription:</strong> Use state-of-the-art automatic speech recognition (ASR) to handle various accents and background noise.</li>
    <li><strong>Contextual Diarization:</strong> Separate agent and customer channels, even on single-track audio recordings.</li>
    <li><strong>Actionable Feedback:</strong> Provide supervisors with clear, context-aware coaching insights.</li>
    <li><strong>Data Privacy:</strong> Implement transient lifecycle management for audio uploads.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 4 ================= -->
  <h1>2. Core Architecture & Modular System Topography</h1>
  <p>
    The platform is built on a clean decoupling of the client-side user interface from the backend API services. This separation ensures that the UI remains highly responsive even during heavy audio processing tasks on the server.
  </p>
  
  <h3>System Topology Directory Mapping:</h3>
  <pre>
c:\Users\shubh\Desktop\call agent
├── server.js                 # Express Application Entry Point
├── package.json              # Project Dependencies and NPM Scripts
├── public/                   # Frontend Client Static Directory
│   ├── index.html            # UI Structure and Modals Markup
│   ├── styles.css            # Cyberpunk Glass Theme System & Animations
│   ├── app.js                # State Controller, Renderers & 3D Tilt Script
│   └── observe-logo.jpg      # Yellow Brand Identity Asset
├── uploads/                  # Temporary Audio Processing Workspace
└── src/                      # Backend Core Business Logic
    ├── storage.js            # In-Memory DB and Retrieval Interface
    ├── detection.js          # Regex and Lexicon Moment Validation Engine
    ├── summary.js            # Quantitative Metric Aggregator
    ├── groqAI.js             # Whisper STT and Llama 3.3 Integration Router
    └── routes/
        └── calls.js          # REST Router Handlers
  </pre>

  <p>
    This component layout isolates the backend processing from the UI. If you want to change the database from in-memory storage to PostgreSQL, you only need to modify <code>storage.js</code>. The rest of the application remains untouched.
  </p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 5 ================= -->
  <h1>3. Diarized Voice Intelligence Pipeline</h1>
  <p>
    Handling single-track audio recordings requires a multi-step diarization pipeline. In dual-track call recordings, the agent and customer speak on separate audio channels. However, on single-track channels, they are mixed together. The Call Quality Review Tool resolves this using a combination of Whisper's timestamp offsets and Llama 3.3's linguistic analysis:
  </p>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <div class="highlight-box-title">Process Flow: Audio to Structured Transcript</div>
    <p>
      1. **Audio Ingestion:** The supervisor uploads an audio recording (MP3, WAV, etc.) to the <code>/calls/upload</code> endpoint.<br>
      2. **ASR Processing:** The file is streamed to <strong>Groq Whisper Large v3</strong>, which returns transcription segments containing absolute timestamps.<br>
      3. **Contextual Diarization:** The raw segments are forwarded to <strong>Llama 3.3</strong> on Groq. Llama acts as an intelligent classifier, labeling each block as <code>"agent"</code> or <code>"customer"</code> based on greeting phrases, professional greetings, customer complaints, and context.<br>
      4. **Analytical Compilation:** The labeled transcript is stored and analyzed to extract moments, talk ratios, and empathy scores.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Llama 3.3 Diarization System Prompt:</h3>
  <p>
    To ensure consistent results, Llama 3.3 is configured with a strict system prompt:
  </p>
  <pre>
You are an expert diarization assistant. Your task is to analyze transcription segments and determine whether the speaker is the "agent" or the "customer".
Analyze greetings, phrasing, compliance words, and conversational flow.
Output your classification exclusively in the following JSON format:
[
  { "speaker": "agent", "text": "...", "t": 0 },
  { "speaker": "customer", "text": "...", "t": 12 }
]
Do not include any intro or outro text. Output raw JSON only.
  </pre>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 6 ================= -->
  <h1>4. Rules-Based Moment Detection Engine</h1>
  <p>
    The moment detection engine in <code>src/detection.js</code> uses local string analysis and math logic gates to process transcripts instantly. This approach is much faster than running analysis through external APIs.
  </p>

  <h2>4.1. Escalation Signals</h2>
  <p>
    Escalations highlight call friction, customer frustration, or compliance risks. The engine checks customer dialogue turns against a set of key terms:
  </p>
  <pre>
const ESCALATION_WORDS = ['refund', 'ridiculous', 'unacceptable', 'manager', 'cancel', 'lawsuit'];
  </pre>
  <p>
    If a customer segment contains any of these words, the engine flags it and records the matching term to highlight it in the frontend transcript view.
  </p>

  <h2>4.2. Empathy Statements</h2>
  <p>
    Empathy is a key metric for customer satisfaction. The engine scans agent turns for active listening and validation statements:
  </p>
  <pre>
const EMPATHY_PATTERNS = ["i understand", "i'm sorry", "i apologise", "i apologize", "i can see why"];
  </pre>
  <p>
    Unlike escalations, the engine counts multiple empathy phrases in a single turn separately. For example, if an agent says, *"I completely understand your frustration and I'm very sorry about the delay,"* both "understand" and "sorry" are flagged as separate moments.
  </p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 7 ================= -->
  <h2>4.3. Long Monologues</h2>
  <p>
    Long monologues from either the agent or the customer can indicate communication issues. For example, an agent monologue might mean they are over-explaining or reading too much of a script, while a customer monologue might indicate a complex complaint.
  </p>
  <p>
    The monologue checker monitors word counts within consecutive turns. The segment text is split by whitespace:
  </p>
  <pre>
const wordCount = turn.text.split(/\s+/).filter(Boolean).length;
if (wordCount >= 120) {
  // Flag as a monologue
}
  </pre>
  <p>
    If a turn contains **120 words or more**, it is flagged as a monologue.
  </p>

  <h2>4.4. Dead Air & Speaker Transitions</h2>
  <p>
    Dead air refers to silent gaps in a conversation. These gaps often point to tool delays, slow search queries, or confusion during the call.
  </p>
  <p>
    The engine monitors timestamps between turns. The gap is calculated as:
  </p>
  <pre>
const gap = currentTurn.t - (previousTurn.t + estimatedPreviousDuration);
if (gap >= 15) {
  // Flag as dead air
}
  </pre>
  <p>
    If the silence last **15 seconds or more**, it is flagged as dead air. The moment is attached to the turn where conversation resumes, making it easy for supervisors to skip directly to the point where speech starts again.
  </p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

  <!-- ================= PAGE 8 ================= -->
  <h1>5. REST API Endpoints Specification</h1>
  <p>
    The backend router in <code>src/routes/calls.js</code> exposes a set of REST endpoints to handle audio files and JSON datasets:
  </p>

  <h3>1. POST /calls</h3>
  <p>
    Ingests raw JSON transcripts. Ideal for importing third-party datasets.
  </p>
  <pre>
Request Body:
{
  "id": "call_99",
  "agentName": "Alice Johnson",
  "timestamp": "2026-06-20T11:00:00Z",
  "duration": 180,
  "transcript": [
    { "speaker": "agent", "text": "Hello, how can I help you?", "t": 0 }
  ]
}
Response: 201 Created
{
  "callId": "call_99",
  "momentCount": 0
}
  </pre>

  <h3>2. POST /calls/upload</h3>
  <p>
    Uploads call audio files. The server uses Multer to handle the upload, streams it to Groq Whisper, diarizes the speakers, runs moment detection, and saves the results.
  </p>

  <h3>3. DELETE /calls/:id</h3>
  <p>
    Permanently deletes a call recording and its analysis.
  </p>
  <pre>
Response: 200 OK
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Call \"call_99\" deleted successfully."
}
  </pre>

  <div class="page-break"></div>

